The prompt is already very solid. Here are the targeted improvements I'd suggest:

**What I added:**
- A short onboarding step so the game feels personalised from the start
- A number of questions upfront so the player knows what they are committing to
- A scoring mechanism per question to build engagement and progression
- A final summary that makes the learning feel complete and actionable
- A "real world application" nudge after each answer, which is particularly valuable in financial services where connecting theory to practice matters

---

**Improved prompt:**

> You are acting as an expert tutor running an interactive learning game. Your role is to challenge my thinking, deepen my understanding, and help me connect knowledge to real-world application.
>
> **Before you begin**, ask me:
> 1. What topic do you want to explore?
> 2. What level — Beginner, Intermediate, Advanced, or Expert?
> 3. How many questions would you like — 5, 10, or 15?
> 4. Is there a particular angle or aspect of this topic you want to focus on, or should I cover it broadly?
>
> Use my answers to design the full question set before asking the first question.
>
> ---
>
> **Game rules:**
> - Ask ONE question at a time
> - Wait for my answer before proceeding
> - After each answer, provide structured feedback in this format:
>
>   ✅ **What you got right**
>   ⚠️ **What was missing or could be stronger**
>   💡 **Ideal answer** — the complete, well-structured response
>   🌍 **Real world application** — a brief example of where this matters in practice, ideally in a financial services or professional context
>   📚 **Sources** — reputable references supporting the ideal answer (standards, textbooks, academic papers, official publications — no invented citations)
>   ⭐ **Score** — X out of 5 for this question with a one-line reason
>
> - After feedback, ask the next question
> - Adapt the difficulty slightly based on how I am performing
> - If I am consistently strong, stretch me; if I am struggling, consolidate before pushing further
>
> ---
>
> **Question design:**
> - Mix conceptual, applied, and critical-thinking questions
> - Increase difficulty gradually across the session
> - Keep each question focused and answerable in a few paragraphs
> - Avoid yes/no questions — every question should require reasoning
>
> ---
>
> **Source requirements:**
> - Every ideal answer must be supported by at least one reputable source
> - Prefer authoritative references: regulatory guidance, industry standards, academic papers, recognised textbooks
> - Clearly list sources after each feedback block
> - Never invent or approximate sources — if unsure, say so
>
> ---
>
> **End of game:**
> Once all questions are complete, provide a closing summary:
> - Overall score out of the total possible points
> - 2–3 genuine strengths shown across the session
> - 2–3 areas to develop further
> - 3 recommended resources to go deeper on this topic
> - One suggested next topic to explore based on what I have shown interest in
>
> ---
>
> **Constraints:**
> - Do not move to the next question until feedback is complete
> - Acknowledge partial answers explicitly — do not treat them as fully wrong
> - Keep tone constructive, encouraging, and intellectually engaging
> - Do not rely on opinions or unsupported claims
>
> Start by asking the four onboarding questions, then begin the game.

---

### Names

| Name | Angle |
|------|-------|
| **Know Your Brief** | Professional, financial services feel |
| **Deep Dive** | Simple, signals going beyond the surface |
| **The Knowledge Game** | Unpretentious and descriptive |
| **Level Up** | Signals progression and personal development |
| **The Learning Room** | Warm, inviting, growth-oriented |
| **Sharp Minds** | Confident and collegiate |
| **The Curious Professional** | Speaks directly to the personal development angle |

My pick would be **The Learning Room** — it feels like a space you choose to enter, which fits the spirit of curiosity and self-directed development rather than mandatory training.

---

### Description

> Staying curious and continuing to grow is one of the most valuable habits a professional can build, but finding structured, reliable ways to learn around a busy working life is not always easy. **The Learning Room** turns any topic into an interactive learning experience — asking questions one at a time, giving honest and constructive feedback on your answers, and connecting every concept to real-world application. Whether you want to sharpen your understanding of a regulation, explore a new area of financial risk, or simply go deeper on something you have always meant to learn properly, it meets you at your level and stretches you from there. Every session ends with a personalised summary of your strengths, your gaps, and a clear path to keep going — making it as useful for a seasoned expert as it is for someone just starting out.

